<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">41692196</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>12</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>12</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1879-0003</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>349</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of biological macromolecules</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Biol Macromol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Design and characterization of banana pseudostem-derived cellulose nanofibrous gel for topical delivery of ketoconazole.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>150923</StartPage><MedlinePgn>150923</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2026.150923</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0141-8130(26)00849-4</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Cellulose nanofibers (CNFs) were extracted from banana pseudostem using an alkali acid hydrolysis method and evaluated for their potential application in topical drug delivery. Compositional analysis confirmed a high cellulose content (94.13&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;2.12%) with minimal hemicellulose (4.15&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;3.21%) and lignin (0.71&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;0.54%). Dynamic light scattering revealed a particle size of 240.8&#xa0;nm, PDI of 0.341, and a zeta potential of -29&#xa0;mV, while scanning and transmission electron microscopy demonstrated nanoscale dimensions (~55&#xa0;nm diameter) with high crystallinity and thermal stability. The aqueous dispersion of extracted CNFs and Carbopol 934P were mixed with ketoconazole solution to form ketoconazole-loaded nanofibrous gel system. The formulation was optimized using a two-factor, three-level central composite design, yielding an optimized composition of 1% w/v CNFs, 0.5% w/v Carbopol 934P, and 2% w/v ketoconazole. The optimized nanogel exhibited neutral pH, high viscosity, excellent spreadability, thermal stability, and an amorphous drug dispersion. In vitro release showed 99.70% ketoconazole release, while ex vivo permeation studies demonstrated enhanced skin diffusion (42.31&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;1.74%) within 360&#xa0;min. The formulation displayed significant antibacterial activity against S. aureus and E. coli and antifungal activity against Candida albicans (23.0&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;0.2&#xa0;mm inhibition zone). Biocompatibility assessment using Vero cells and histopathological evaluation confirmed non-cytotoxicity and absence of skin irritation respectively. This study provides new insight into the valorization of banana pseudostem agro-waste as a sustainable and stable nanofibrous carrier, addressing critical gaps in eco-friendly, effective, and safe topical antifungal drug delivery systems.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bhatia</LastName><ForeName>Meenakshi</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Guru Jambheshwar University of Science and Technology, Hisar, 125001, Haryana, India. Electronic address: meenaxibhatia@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kumar</LastName><ForeName>Dinesh</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>GNA School of Pharmacy, GNA University, Phagwara, 147301, Punjab, India. Electronic address: dineshpotlia123@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Arora</LastName><ForeName>Sandeep</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amity Institute of Pharmacy, Amity University, Mohali, 140306, Punjab, India. Electronic address: sand_orbbd@rediffmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>P